als of physical mortification and sexual license, committed suicides in the throes of materialist fatalism, drank potions to induce consciousness-altering dreams, railed against the degrading effects of unfettered consumption, and ultimately renounced the feudal privileges that had for centuries defined their social existence. The explosive denouement was the French Revolution, during which God and king were toppled from their thrones.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aEnlightenmentxFrancexFrance. 0aEnlightenmentzFrance. 0aIndividualismxHistoryx18th centuryxFrance. 0aIndividualismzFrancexHistoryy18th century. 0aPhilosophy, Frenchx18th century. 0aPhilosophy, Frenchy18th century. 0aSelf (Philosophy)xHistoryx18th centuryxFrance. 0aSelf (Philosophy)zFrancexHistoryy18th century. 4aFrench Enlightenment. 4aFrench Revolution. 4adispossession. 4adream-state. 4aluxury consumption. 4amaterialism. 4amysticism. 4arepublicanism. 4aself-ownership. 4aself. 7aHISTORY / Europe / France.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311070398640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080479121240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804791212423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804791212.jpg  a978-3-11-070398-6  SUP Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles